Church, Mendham, Norfolk, England":"Mendham, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Freston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Freestone  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Freestone","meanings":["English: habitational name from Friston or Freston (both Suffolk), Frieston (Lincolnshire), or possibly Friston (Sussex)."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":35,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Richard Freston was born about 1514, in Mendham, Norfolk, England, his father, Robert, was 11 and his mother, Freston, was -44. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Anne Coke. He died in 1557, at the age of 44, and was buried in Mendham, Norfolk, England."},"et":{"abt. 1514–1557":"umbes 1514–1557","1514–1557":"1514–1557","1587–Female":"1587–Surnud","1515–1557":"1515–1557","1529–1568":"1529–1568","1550–1616":"1550–1616","1504–Male":"1504–Surnud","1560–Female":"1560–Surnud","abt. 1514":"umbes 1514","before 1557":"enne 1557","1550":"1550","1560":"1560","1514":"1514","19 November 1550":"19. november 1550","1557":"1557","1568":"1568","1587":"1587","1553":"1553","1529":"1529","1616":"1616","1549":"1549","1504":"1504","1515":"1515","Wingfield, Suffolk, England":"Wingfield, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Clavering, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Clavering, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Mendham, Norfolk, England":"Mendham, Norfolk, England","Mendham Church, Mendham, Norfolk, England":"Mendham, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"abt. 1514–1557":"noin 1514–1557","1514–1557":"1514–1557","1587–Female":"1587–Kuollut","1515–1557":"1515–1557","1529–1568":"1529–1568","1550–1616":"1550–1616","1504–Male":"1504–Kuollut","1560–Female":"1560–Kuollut","abt. 1514":"noin 1514","before 1557":"ennen vuotta 1557","1550":"1550","1560":"1560","1514":"1514","19 November 1550"